googleReviewsBySlug.json.name: Andre Davis
googleReviewsBySlug.json.text:
Referred to S&S via my home warranty provider for repairs to my sump grinder pump. Technician was dispatched the very next day (Friday) and assessed the repair. Not including the service call fee, I was charged $250 to simply pump out the water from the holding tank. Was then charged to make the repairs and paid a final bill of $950. I would break down this total for you but I asked multiple times for a detailed invoice and was promised that one would be emailed to me, but I never received it. Two days later (Sunday) same issue started again and technician returned on Monday. Technician then stated  that I need a new sump pump with an estimated cost of $3500.

Made the decision to contact my local utility company for input. Utility company dispatched a service tech immediately. Per utility company, I should have never contacted a private plumber since my home is connected to the utility sewar line. Utility company tech also looked at repairs supposedly done by S&S tech and stated they had to "correct" what he had attempted to do. Now, I understand that techs do things differently, but I just wanted to share what was told to me. Utility company tech repaired my sump grinder pump for a very fair price of $525...no new grinder pump required, only a couple of parts.

From my perspective, S&S technician knew that I was not personally responsible for this repair and at most, I should have been charged a service call fee and/or diagnostic fee. When the S&S technician initially came to my home, I showed him a phone number on my sump pump alarm box and asked him if I should call them. He replied that he did not know why that message was on the box. Looking back, I should have followed my initial instinct to call.

My MAJOR issue with this vendor is that I am convinced that they knew that the utility company was responsible but instead treated this repair as if I as the owner should pay. In addition, still not clear how a final repair was done for $525 and S&S had me on the hook for nearly $4400 ($950 + $3450). When speaking with the utility company, even if I did need a brand new pump, the estimated cost was $1000 less that the S&S quote.

Again, while S&S did attempt to make the repairs for me, I just don't feel as if they were looking out for my best interest in their recommendations.
googleReviewsBySlug.json.responseFromOwnerText:
I’m sorry you felt the need to poorly review our business, especially after we got to you on an emergency basis. Let me break it down here for you: there was an emergency diagnostic/trip fee of $300; there was a charge of $350 to evacuate sewage from the pit so the we could even diagnose the pump; there was a $300 charge to reconnect the drain lines that were disconnected because of they were under tension from the original installation position of the discharge line.

I don’t know how how we could have know that a utility board is supposed to be responsible for a sewage pump on your side of the meter, that seems like something a homeowner should be aware of. The utility company must have access to volume pricing on their parts, because my pump supplier couldn’t access the float for the pump you have. The price I quoted you for a new pump installation was a good price. If you had someone who could do it for $1000 less that’s fine, because $2500 doesn’t even cover my price for pump and materials. I’m not sure what more we could have done to serve your best interests, and I would urge you to remove this poor review due to the fact that we did everything within our power to assist you.
